definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To cover, fill, or affect with lead.
examples: continuous firing leads the grooves of a rifle.

definitions.definition: ( transitive , printing , historical ) To place leads between the lines of.

main_definition: ( transitive ) To cover, fill, or affect with lead.
secondary_definitions: ( transitive , printing , historical ) To place leads between the lines of.

definitions.definition: ( heading , transitive ) To guide or conduct .

subdefinitions.definition: To guide or conduct with the hand, or by means of some physical contact connection.
examples: a jockey leads a horse with a halter
a dog leads a blind man

subdefinitions.definition: To guide or conduct in a certain course , or to a certain place or end, by making the way known; to show the way, especially by going with or going in advance of, to lead a pupil; to guide somebody somewhere or to bring somebody somewhere by means of instructions .
examples: The guide was able to lead the tourists through the jungle safely.

subdefinitions.definition: ( figuratively ) : To direct ; to counsel ; to instruct
examples: A good teacher should lead their students to the right answer.

subdefinitions.definition: To conduct or direct with authority ; to have direction or charge of; to command , especially a military or business unit.

To guide or conduct oneself in, through, or along (a certain course); hence, to proceed in the way of; to follow the path or course of; to pass; to spend. Also, to cause (one) to proceed or follow in (a certain course).
examples: The evidence leads me to believe he is guilty.

definitions.definition: ( intransitive ) To guide or conduct, as by accompanying, going before, showing, influencing, directing with authority, etc.; to have precedence or preeminence; to be first or chief ; — used in most of the senses of the transitive verb.
( heading ) To begin, to be ahead.

subdefinitions.definition: ( transitive ) To go or to be in advance of; to precede ; hence, to be foremost or chief among.
examples: the big sloop led the fleet of yachts;  the Guards led the attack;  Demosthenes leads the orators of all ages

subdefinitions.definition: ( intransitive ) To proceed in front of others; to go first.
examples: The standard-bearers led and the rest of the marchers followed.

subdefinitions.definition: ( intransitive ) To be more advanced in technology or business than others.
examples: It leads in the information technology sector.

subdefinitions.definition: ( heading , sports ) ( transitive , card games , dominoes ) To begin a game, round, or trick, with ( intransitive ) To be ahead of others, e.g., in a race . ( intransitive ) To have the highest interim score in a game . ( baseball ) To step off base and move towards the next base. ( shooting ) To aim in front of a moving target , in order that the shot may hit the target as it passes. ( transitive , climbing ) Lead climb .
examples: He led the ace of spades.
The batter always leads off base.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To draw or direct by influence , whether good or bad; to prevail on; to induce ; to entice; to allure
examples: to lead someone to a righteous cause

definitions.definition: ( intransitive ) To tend or reach in a certain direction , or to a certain place.
examples: the path leads to the mill;  gambling leads to other vices

definitions.definition: ( transitive , usually with " life " ) To live or experience (a particular way of life).
Used in phrasal verbs: lead off , lead on , lead out , lead to ( “ be the cause of, bring about ” ) , lead up , lead up to .
